## suivi chiros
- acoustic monitoring
- nacelle
- bats 
- bat monitoring
In parallel of fatality searches, bat activity is also monitored at nacelle height in order to understand better in which weather conditions bats are active throughout the seasons. This has been useful to work out bat curtailment plans specifically for each site.

After having filtered out noises, all the remaining sound files are counted and then correlated to weather conditions (wind speed and temperature at least). Most of these bat passes are recorded for wind speed below 6 m/s (see this French study compiling 3 years of monitoring at height on measuring masts [Labouré et al. 2020](http://www.museum-bourges.net/documents/laboure_m._et_al._-_analyse_activite_des_cs_en_fonction_meteo.pdf)). Au-delà de 8 m/s, l'activité des chiroptères résiduelle est très faible, et correspond à des grosses espèces migratrices (noctules notamment). L'activité des chiroptères augmente avec la température, particulièrement entre 10°C et 25°C.

![](https://media.giphy.com/media/9gqC3kr1MEwxK9YP6T/giphy.gif)
